Maecenas was an author, though probably an indifferent one3 and Horace may have put off his request that he should write a poetical account of Augustus’ achievements by suggesting that he should write one in prose. It does not follow that Maecenas ever wrote or that Horace ever seriously intended to advise his writing. ‘ Pede- stribus' is an adaptation of the Greek πεζὸς λόγος for ‘ prose‚' or ‘ soluta oratio,’ which latter was the usual expression for prose in Horace’s time. P. 95) “ tragicus plerumque dolet ser- mone pedestri.'' Quintilian uses the word but expressly as a Graecism (see Forcell.). The word ‘ prosa,’ or ⁴ prorsa,’ as its correct form appears to be, is of later use than the age of Augustus.
